│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                     │
│                                                                                 │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                 │
│ ### 1. Understanding the Issue                                                  │
│                                                                                 │
│ The vectorizer is aborting due to an assertion failure: `VPlan cost model and   │
│ legacy cost model disagreed`. This assertion ensures that the new VPlan-based   │
│ cost model and the older legacy cost model either select the same Vectorization │
│ Factor (VF), or if they differ, the VPlan model's choice is justified by        │
│ additional optimizations it can perform (checked by                             │
│ `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications`). In this case, they disagreed on the   │
│ VF, and the VPlan-based choice was not deemed better.                           │
│                                                                                 │
│ ### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log & Debugger State                                   │
│                                                                                 │
│ The `opt` log and backtrace confirm the crash location is within                │
│ `LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF`. An inspection of the program state   │
│ at the crash point reveals the core of the disagreement:                        │
│                                                                                 │
│ *   `LegacyVF.Width` was `2`. The legacy cost model decided to vectorize with a │
│ factor of 2.                                                                    │
│ *   `BestFactor.Width` was `1`. The VPlan-based cost model decided not to       │
│ vectorize (a factor of 1 means scalar execution).                               │
│                                                                                 │
│ This confirms the disagreement. The VPlan cost model found vectorization to be  │
│ more expensive than scalar execution, while the legacy model found it           │
│ beneficial.                                                                     │
│                                                                                 │
│ ### 3. Root Cause Analysis                                                      │
│                                                                                 │
│ The core of the problem lies in how the loop-invariant value `%add` is handled  │
│ by the two cost models.                                                         │
│                                                                                 │
│ *   In the provided IR, `%add` is computed in the `entry` block from two        │
│ constants: `zext i16 -6 to i64` and `i64 -65528`. This is a foldable expression │
│ that results in the constant value `2`.                                         │
│ *   The legacy cost model, along with other parts of the classic Loop           │
│ Vectorizer, relies on `ScalarEvolution` (SCEV) to analyze expressions. SCEV     │
│ correctly folds the computation and determines that `%add` is the constant `2`. │
│ When costing the `mul` instruction inside the loop, it sees it as a             │
│ multiplication by a constant, which is cheap.                                   │
│ *   The VPlan-based cost model, however, does not use SCEV in the same way      │
│ during its initial costing phase. It sees the `zext` and `add` instructions as  │
│ part of the loop's context, but it doesn't fold them into a constant. Instead,  │
│ it models the cost of broadcasting the live-in value `%add` across the vector   │
│ lanes for each iteration. This broadcasting cost is what makes the VPlan model  │
│ incorrectly conclude that vectorization is more expensive than scalar           │
│ execution.                                                                      │
│                                                                                 │
│ The function `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` is meant to catch          │
│ discrepancies like this, but it also fails to recognize that the VPlan will     │
│ eventually be able to simplify this broadcast away. It doesn't account for the  │
│ fact that the live-in value is derived from constants and can be folded.        │
│                                                                                 │
│ The fix is to enhance `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` to check if a     │
│ live-in value is constant. If it is, we can assume that any associated          │
│ broadcast cost is negligible because the constant can be materialized directly  │
│ in the vector loop, avoiding an expensive broadcast.                            │
│                                                                                 │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                   │
│                                                                                 │
│ The fix involves modifying `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` to correctly │
│ identify and handle constant live-in values.                                    │
│                                                                                 │
│ **File**: `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp`                     │
│                                                                                 │
│ ```cpp                                                                          │
│ // Edit at line 7298                                                            │
│ if (auto *LI = dyn_cast<LiveInValue>(U)) {                                      │
│   Value *V = LI->getLiveInValue();                                              │
│   if (isa<Constant>(V))                                                         │
│     continue;                                                                   │
│   const SCEV *S = CM.SE.getSCEV(V);                                             │
│   if (CM.SE.isLoopInvariant(S, OrigLoop))                                       │
│     continue;                                                                   │
│ }                                                                               │
│ ```                                                                             │
│                                                                                 │
│ This change adds a check within the loop that iterates over users of a recipe.  │
│ If a user is a `LiveInValue`, it checks if the underlying `Value` is a          │
│ `Constant`. If so, it skips to the next user, effectively ignoring the cost     │
│ associated with this live-in, which aligns the VPlan cost assessment with the   │
│ reality of what will happen during code generation.                             │
│                                                                                 │
│ ### 5. Conclusion                                                               │
│                                                                                 │
│ The root cause of the assertion failure was a discrepancy in how the legacy and │
│ VPlan cost models evaluated the cost of a loop-invariant value that is foldable │
│ into a constant. The VPlan model incorrectly added the cost of broadcasting     │
│ this value, leading it to choose a suboptimal vectorization factor. The         │
│ proposed edit corrects this by teaching the VPlan's arbiter function,           │
│ `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications`, to recognize constant live-in values   │
│ and ignore their broadcast costs, resolving the disagreement and allowing       │
│ vectorization to proceed correctly.                                             │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                 │
